\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 33. M. sicula} Guss., {\i Fl. Sic. Syn.}{\b  1}: 214 (1843). Annual or biennial, stems either short and little-branched, or up to 50 cm and much-branched, erect to ascending; hairs on stems and leaves straight, appressed and pointing upwards. Basal leaves 6 × 0·8 cm, broadly linear, usually withering at maturity; cauline ovate-oblong. Inflorescence with flowers in two distinct rows; only the lowermost pedicels longer than the calyx at maturity. Calyx up to 6 mm in fruit; tube twice as long as the scarcely divergent teeth. Limb of corolla up to 3 mm in diameter, saucer-shaped, bright blue. Nutlets 1 mm, ovoid or ellipsoid, dark to medium brown, with appendage on the attachment-area. 2n = 46, 46+2.{\i  Wet places. S. & W. Europe, northwards to N.W. France.} Bu Co Ga Gr Hs It Ju Sa Si Tu.
